<subSubSection id="199ABE63475C14CD39BAA41A90E1ABDF" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CC2A1097560CC74874414368DF7476BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB23BFB2C53C3B41D528FC85A725E0A7" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The most characteristic feature of this species is colouration and shape of the first pair of legs. Tibia I in male is totally black, it is not flattened (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6205DB05BDB21B3B2992E00554AF2103" captionStart="Figures 172–176" captionStartId="F32" captionText="Figures 172 - 176. Peplometus congoensis sp. nov. 172 male, holotype, habitus, dorsal view 173 male, habitus, ventral view 174 female, habitus, dorsal view 175 female, habitus, ventral view 176 female, habitus, lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures172-176" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427084" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">172</figureCitation>
), whereas in congeners tibia is flattened dorsally or laterally and has a light streak or patch. Tibia I of the female is light retrolaterally, with large dark patch at its basis (Figs 
<figureCitation id="918AFEF97206B0678DEA526B02A1AD20" captionStart="Figures 177–183" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figures 177 - 183. Peplometus congoensis sp. nov. 177 palpal organ, ventral view 178 palpal organ, lateral view 179 first leg of female, prolateral view 180 first leg of female, retolateral view 181 epigyne 182 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 183 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures177-183" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427085" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">179</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="CE01021135C2A37909D7AD5A7CE7EED3" captionStart="Figures 177–183" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figures 177 - 183. Peplometus congoensis sp. nov. 177 palpal organ, ventral view 178 palpal organ, lateral view 179 first leg of female, prolateral view 180 first leg of female, retolateral view 181 epigyne 182 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 183 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures177-183" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427085" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">180</figureCitation>
). The abdomen of female is narrow, similar as in male, while females of other species have abdomen wider than males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7F1B59E36DEEED458F89454276A5F5CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="etymology">
